'''Annette Imhausen''' (also known as '''Annette Warner''', born June 12, 1970) is a German [[history of mathematics|historian of mathematics]] known for her work on [[Ancient Egyptian mathematics]]. She is a professor in the Normative Orders Cluster of Excellence at [[Goethe University Frankfurt]].{{r|no}}

==Education and career==
Imhausen studied chemistry at [[Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz]], passing the [[Staatsexamen]] in 1996. She completed her doctorate in the history of mathematics at Mainz in 2002 under the joint supervision of [[David E. Rowe]] and James Ritter.{{r|mgp}}

After teaching the [[Coptic language]] at Mainz in 1998, she worked as an instructor at the [[University of Cambridge]] from 2003 to 2006.
She returned to Mainz as an assistant professor from 2006 to 2008, and became a professor at Frankfurt in 2009.{{r|no}}

==Contributions==
Imhausen is featured in the BBC TV series ''[[The Story of Maths]]''.{{r|imdb}}

Her dissertation, ''Ägyptische Algorithmen. Eine Untersuchung zu den mittelägyptischen mathematischen Aufgabentexten'', was published by Harrassowitz Verlag in 2002 (Ägyptologische Abhandlungen, vol. 65).{{r|no|aa}}
She is also the author of ''Mathematics in Ancient Egypt: A Contextual History'' (Princeton University Press, 2016).{{r|mae}}

