{{About-distinguish2|mathematics|the hair painting [[Hair_highlighting#Hair_painting | technique]]}} 
In [[potential theory]], a mathematical discipline, '''balayage''' (from French: ''[[wiktionary:fr:balayage|balayage]]'' "scanning, sweeping") is a method devised by [[Henri Poincaré]] for reconstructing a [[harmonic function]] in a domain from its values on the boundary of the domain.<ref>{{SpringerEOM| title=Balayage method | id=Balayage_method | oldid=11819 | first=E.D. | last=Solomentsev }}</ref>

In modern terms, the '''balayage operator''' maps a [[Measure (mathematics)|measure]] ''&mu;'' on a closed domain ''D'' to a measure ''&nu;'' on the boundary ''&part; D'', so that the [[Newtonian potential]]s of ''&mu;'' and ''&nu;'' coincide outside ''D''. The procedure is called balayage since the mass is "swept out" from ''D'' onto the boundary.

For ''x'' in ''D'', the balayage of [[Dirac delta function|''&delta;''<sub>''x''</sub>]] yields the [[harmonic measure]] ''&nu;''<sub>''x''</sub> corresponding to ''x''. Then the value of a harmonic function ''f'' at ''x'' is equal to

:<math> f(x) = \int_{\partial D} f(y) \, d\nu_x(y).</math>

