'''LILI-128''' is an [[LFSR]] based [[Synchronization (computer science)|synchronous]] [[stream cipher]] with a 128-bit key. On 13 November 2000, LILI-128 was presented at the [[NESSIE]] workshop.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cosic.esat.kuleuven.be/nessie/workshop/submissions/lili-128.zip | title=NESSIE submission for LILI-128 | date=2000-11-06 | format=zip | accessdate=2018-09-13}}</ref> It is designed to be simple to implement in both software and hardware.
In 2007, LILI-128 was totally broken by using a notebook running [[MATLAB]] in 1.61 hours.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Reconstructing the Nonlinear Filter Function of LILI-128 Stream Cipher Based on Complexity | authors=Xiangao Huang, Wei Huang, Xiaozhou Liu, Chao Wang, Zhu jing Wang, Tao Wang | date=2007-02-22 | url=https://arxiv.org/abs/cs/0702128}}</ref>
